						<div class="postbody">Why do you use those strange names instead of $2006 and $2007? Makes the code completely unreadable to me.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">pubby wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">This has been used before <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=":wink:" title="Wink" /> </div><br />PLA/STA chains, definitely. The RTS I'm not so sure whether it had been used before in this context.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I still prefer zeropage buffers for most updates though.</div><br />Me too, but in some (rare) cases it's not fast enough.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Popslides are still slower than in-ram LDA #xx \ STA $2007 slides.</div><br />LDA #imm / STA $2006 is about the fasest you can go, the only faster possibility is to include clever use of X and Y register for 2 most common values and avoid a LDA here; also some clever usage of INX/INY/DEX/DEY/LSR/ASL/ROL/ROR will be the same speed but with less bytes. I think Tokumaru already made a thread about that. Since generating such code in RAM would be difficult, it was mostly intended at staying in ROM, even if this eats a lot of it.</div>

